│ This is an interesting bug in the `ConstraintElimination`    │
│ pass. The root cause analysis is spot on: the pass           │
│ incorrectly applies a simplification rule that is valid for  │
│ a standard `or` but not for a `disjoint or`. The `disjoint`  │
│ keyword asserts that at most one operand can be true, and    │
│ violating this turns the result into `poison`. The           │
│ optimization was breaking this assertion.                    │
│                                                              │
│ My plan is to disable this specific optimization for `or     │
│ disjoint` instructions within the                            │
│ `checkOrAndOpImpliedByOther` function. The key is to         │
│ correctly identify a `disjoint or`. The                      │
│ `PossiblyDisjointInst` class is designed for this. An `or`   │
│ instruction can be cast to `PossiblyDisjointInst`, which has │
│ an `isDisjoint()` method.                                    │
│                                                              │
│ I will add a check at the beginning of                       │
│ `checkOrAndOpImpliedByOther`. If the instruction is an `or`  │
│ and it has the `disjoint` attribute, the function will bail  │
│ out, preventing the incorrect transformation. This is a      │
│ targeted fix that should resolve the bug without affecting   │
│ optimizations on regular `or` and `and` instructions.        │
│                                                              │
